In Spring Cloud Gateway it is possible to directly retrieve the path params from the custom filter.
In order to do that, it is needed to create a class that implements GatewayFilter.

    @Component
    public class TestFilter implements GatewayFilter {

        @Override
        public Mono&lt;Void&gt; filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {

            Map&lt;String, String&gt; pathParams = exchange.getAttribute(ServerWebExchangeUtils.URI_TEMPLATE_VARIABLES_ATTRIBUTE);
        
            //... do your logic

            return chain.filter(exchange);
        }
    }

Inside this class, it is possible to retrieve the path params using the following lines of code:

    Map&lt;String, String&gt; pathParams = exchange.getAttribute(ServerWebExchangeUtils.URI_TEMPLATE_VARIABLES_ATTRIBUTE);


Inside your RouteConfig class, you can define a path with path params in this way:

    @Configuration
    public class RouteConfig {

    @Bean
    public RouteLocator gatewayRoutes(RouteLocatorBuilder builder) {
        return builder.routes()
                .route(r -&gt; r.path(&quot;/auth/api/auth/{param1}/test/{param2}&quot;)
                        .filters(f -&gt; f.filter(new TestFilter()))
                        .uri(&quot;lb://AUTH-SERVICE&quot;))
                .build();
        }
    }

In this case, hitting the url http://localhost:8080/auth/api/auth/signin/test/user1 will result in having the following map inside the custom filter TestFilter:

